Name: Graham, Lindsey
text:
To be crystal clear: As Senate Budget Committee Chairman, I will be working with Stephen Miller and the rest of President Trump’s team to pass — through reconciliation — the most transformational border security bill in American history. 

Democrats had 4 years to deal with this issue and failed. The American people have given Republicans control of the White House, Senate and House. 

Republicans will use reconciliation to transform a broken border. 

We will:

✅ Hire more ICE agents to deport gang members and violent criminals.

✅ Create more bed space so we don’t have to release illegal aliens into the country.

✅ Finish the wall and invest in border security tech to secure a broken border.

✅ Help a beleaguered military and implement common sense energy policy. 

It will be paid for and it will be done quickly. 

I have never seen so many threats to our homeland as I do today. 200 Americans die each day due to fentanyl poisoning. 

Every day we delay transforming our border is a disastrous day for America. 

We are going to transform our border through reconciliation within weeks, not months.

Name: Collins, Mike
text:
On #ThisDayInHistory in 1972, the Apollo lunar program concluded with the safe return of Apollo 17's crew, marking the final manned moon landing. 

Apollo 17 had launched from Cape Canaveral 10 days earlier and its crew, including commander Eugene Cernan, lunar module pilot Harrison Schmitt, and command module pilot Ronald Evans, made significant scientific contributions during their mission. Schmitt, a geologist, became the first scientist-astronaut to land on the moon. The crew spent 75 hours on the lunar surface, conducting three surface excursions in the Lunar Rover and collecting 243 pounds of rock and soil samples.

From 1969 to 1972, NASA successfully carried out six lunar landings, with Apollo 13 being the only mission to be aborted. Apollo 17 remains the most successful and longest manned lunar mission, yielding groundbreaking scientific discoveries and capturing one of the most iconic images of Earth from space.

Name: Mace, Nancy
text:
For decades, Democrats AND Republicans have engaged in massive reckless spending. This cycle of fiscal abuse must come to an end.

If we learned nothing else from the November 5th election, we learned the American people don’t want business as usual in Washington.

They want strong leaders who will stand up and say enough is enough.

I am standing up for my home state of South Carolina and every hardworking American fed up with Washington. 

We need a complete and total reset. A 30-day government shutdown is a good place to start. We can pick this back up after Trump is sworn into office.

Truthfully, a shutdown isn’t a shutdown. That’s a bs lie from the media and the establishment stoking fear in your face.

During a “government shutdown” the president has authority to prioritize spending; the Office of Management and Budget has a contingency plan to prioritize spending; and all mandatory spending is still funded (social security, veterans benefits, Medicare, Medicaid, etc.).

I also have a bill called the Government Shutdown Prevention Act of 2023. This bill would provide immediate stability by appropriating funding for 90 days at 99% of our current budget, with a gradual reduction of 1% per day thereafter.

It’s time to hold the line for our fellow country men and women, for our nation’s future and for future generations.

Shut it down.

#HoldTheLine

Name: Hirono, Mazie K.
text:
The Thomas R. Carper Water Resources Development Act (WRDA) of 2024 passed both Chambers and is headed to @POTUS to be signed into law. Here are key provisions @SenBrianSchatz and I secured for Hawaii:

1⃣ Maui Wildfire Response:
- Prioritize Maui watershed assessments in recommending construction or modification of water resources development projects.
- Create a new project to conduct a feasibility study for flood risk management and ecosystem restoration in the County of Maui.
- Carry out a post-disaster watershed assessment for areas impacted by the August 2023 wildfires on Maui.

2⃣Expand Access to Resources:
- Allow U.S. Army Corps of Engineers to partner with stakeholders on a broader range of projects including cultural resources preservation and environmental restoration.
- Expand remote and subsistence harbors eligibility.
- Create an avenue for remote, coastal areas to include comprehensive cultural, social, and ecosystem benefits in cost-benefit analyses for small hurricane and storm damage reduction projects.

3⃣Strengthen Disaster Resilience:
- Expand scope to consider disaster resilience and enhanced national security from utilization of the Honolulu harbor by the Department of Defense.
- Expedite the completion of the repairs of the damaged seawall at Laupahoehoe Harbor.
- Modify the current Hanapepe Levee project to evaluate sources of flooding and propose engineering and non-structural solutions to reduce flood damages in the Hanapepe River watershed.
- Modify the current Waimea project to evaluate sources of flooding in the Waimea River watershed and investigate modifications to existing Waimea River levees on the southwest coast of Kauai.
- Authorize a new project to conduct a feasibility study for flood risk management in Hawaii Kai.

Name: Hirono, Mazie K.
text:
WRDA is crucial legislation to strengthen our country’s water conservation efforts and improve waterways.

I'll continue fighting to ensure Hawaii has the federal support necessary to enhance our waterway infrastructure and improve disaster resilience efforts.

Name: Fong, Vince
text:
Rep. Vince Fong’s Statement on the Continuing Resolution to Fund the Government through March

Rep. Vince Fong (CA-20) issued the following statement after the “American Relief Act” was voted on by the House tonight and failed to pass by a vote of 174-235-1. 
 
“I had serious concerns with the first CR introduced with the extraneous and questionable provisions that were jammed inside and which I simply could not support. Clearly, we need more transparency in our government. Because of the inaction by Senator Schumer and the Senate who refused to pass any appropriations bills this year, it has created this last-minute mess, holding needed disaster and agricultural relief hostage so the Democrats could obtain many questionable provisions. The new CR agreement - the American Relief Act - focused on the basics and was the first of many steps to change how Washington works. Unfortunately, Democrats have chosen to ignore the needs of the American people right before Christmas and the holiday season and caused the bill to fail. I am hopeful we will come to an agreement that will allow us to tackle our nation’s most pressing challenges and, along with the Trump-Vance Administration, Make America Great Again.”

Name: Van Duyne, Beth
text:
No one should be surprised by my no vote. I have never supported this level of government spending since I have been in office. Voting against this enormous deficit spending is consistent with what I have promised the people of the 24th District I would do. I truly believe government spending is out of control and has led us to record-breaking inflation, the highest debt in our nation’s history, and pernicious federal intrusion into the lives of Americans. 

This past November, the American people spoke clearly, saying they wanted to end massive federal overspending which has driven painful and enduring inflation that is profoundly harming our families and businesses.  

I have tremendous faith that a 2nd Trump Administration coupled with Republican majorities in the House and Senate, will allow us to make major reforms to slash federal spending and job-killing regulations while delivering tax cuts to empower the kind of growth we need to expand our way out of budget deficits as well as make progress against the national debt.  

Unfortunately, at present, Joe Biden and radical Democrats still hold power in the Executive Branch and the Senate and I have no intention of giving them license to continue wasting the precious, hard earned tax dollars of the American people.

Name: Smith, Adam
text:
I voted against the partisan Republican proposal today because it was created solely to serve Musk and Trump, not the American people.

Trump and Musk are holding the U.S. government hostage to personally improve their standing. Musk intervened to protect himself from a China provision that would hurt his business interests. And Trump insisted on raising the debt ceiling so that he would be able to make a massive tax cut for billionaires and CEOs as soon as he gets into office in 2025.

The real tragedy here is that House Republicans are going along with this every step of the way. They have decided to protect Elon Musk’s business interests around China instead of funding childhood cancer research or improving child welfare services. They are prioritizing billionaires over substance-use disorder treatment, 9/11 responder and survivor health funding, workforce development programming, and seniors’ health and wellness services.

This failed bill cuts critical funding that working families are counting on, raises prescription drug costs for hardworking American taxpayers, and makes it easier for CEOs and billionaires to ship jobs overseas.

More than anything we are facing a shutdown because of Mike Johnson’s refusal to pass appropriations bills and fund the government the way it’s supposed to be funded. We should not be getting to the point where we need a Continuing Resolution to avoid a shutdown.

We should pass normal appropriations bills. But the reason we are not passing appropriations bills is the same reason that Mike Johnson allowed Trump and Musk to force forward their own self-interested proposal: he kowtows to the extreme, far-right MAGA Republicans in his conference.

We have the votes to pass normal appropriations bills and that should be our next step. I am deeply concerned that Johnson will not bring the appropriations bills up because MAGA extremists control him.

I urge my colleagues across the aisle to find a bipartisan, common-sense compromise to keep our government funded responsibly.

Name: Collins, Mike
text:
On #ThisDayInHistory in 1957, Elvis Presley, at the height of his fame, received his draft notice for the U.S. Army while spending Christmas at Graceland. 

Elvis had become a cultural icon with hits like “Heartbreak Hotel,” “Hound Dog,” and “Blue Suede Shoes,” making him the first true rock-and-roll star. Despite thousands of fans petitioning for his exemption, Presley chose to serve. After a brief deferment to finish his film *King Creole*, he was sworn in as an army private.

Presley completed basic training and was then stationed in Friedberg, Germany, where he served with the 32nd Tank Battalion, rising to the rank of sergeant. During his time overseas, he lived with his family and hosted frequent parties and jam sessions. It was at one of these gatherings that he met Priscilla Beaulieu, whom he would later marry. Meanwhile, his manager, Colonel Tom Parker, ensured Elvis stayed in the public eye by releasing previously recorded singles, keeping the money flowing and his fame intact.

Name: Mace, Nancy
text:
On the debt ceiling:

Suspending the debt ceiling entirely at this point would allow Congress to add an unlimited amount of debt to our already $36 trillion national debt for two years, with no reforms to rein in reckless spending. 

Suspensions or increases to the debt limit must be paired with spending cuts. I look forward to working with President Trump to enact the steep spending cuts ($1 to $3 trillion) paired with a responsible debt ceiling increase — through reconciliation. 

If we are going to raise the debt ceiling it should be paired dollar for dollar with Trump’s agenda to ensure the Washington establishment can’t skirt the America First agenda and go back on a handshake deal (which they always do).

If I’ve learned one thing from my time in the House, it’s that members of Congress on both sides of the aisle cannot be trusted with a limitless credit card to spend American taxpayer dollars.

Name: Smith, Adam
text:
On September 6, Ayşenur Ezgi Eygi was fatally shot in the West Bank while she was peacefully participating in a demonstration against Israeli settlements in the Palestinian village of Beita. Since then, we have requested an independent, thorough, credible, and transparent investigation into what happened that day to both better understand the circumstances of her death and ensure that if any laws were broken, those who were responsible are held to account.

This week, Ms. Eygi’s family came to D.C. to discuss the challenges they've faced and the questions they still have about what happened. The lack of answers they have received is unacceptable.

We call on Israel to complete their investigation and release their report on the cause of her death. Secretary Blinken must insist on the release of any Israeli investigation results.  We also continue to urge the U.S. Department of Justice to initiate an independent, U.S.-led investigation into Ms. Eygi’s death. If the Justice Department isn’t going to investigate, then the State Department should release their own findings and seek accountability.

Prime Minister Netanyahu and his government have exacerbated tensions in the West Bank with their promotion of rapid Israeli settlement expansion. This dangerous situation in the West Bank has claimed the lives of far too many civilians, including Ms. Eygi.

We applaud the sanctions that President Biden has imposed thus far on extremist Israeli settlers, including the settler organization Amana. Clearly, more must be done.  The policies of Prime Minister Netanyahu’s government undermine the viability of a Palestinian state and Israel’s security, violate the rights of Palestinians living in the West Bank, and put the region at even greater risk of further destabilization.

It is time for the Biden Administration to thoroughly investigate the shooting of Ms. Eygi.

Name: Davis, Donald G.
text:
Friday in the First
 
Roger Edwards, a proud resident of Rocky Mount, NC, has dedicated his life to uplifting his community through his work and volunteer efforts. As the leader of the Adult Day Services program, Roger focuses on empowering individuals with disabilities by emphasizing their unique abilities and ensuring they can live more independent lives.
 
With over 24 years in this field, Roger's passion extends beyond his professional work. He leads the Good News Community Youth Ministry, teaching underprivileged youth the values of service and kindness. As a volunteer Chaplain for "The Rewritten Story Foundation," Roger provides emotional and spiritual support to families affected by natural disasters.  
 
His impact is felt throughout the region. From maintaining the lawns of elderly cancer patients at no cost to ensuring a family could spend Christmas together in comfort, Roger embodies the spirit of selfless service. His efforts have been recognized through grants awarded to support seniors and individuals with disabilities, further cementing his commitment to making a difference.
 
Roger’s unwavering dedication inspires compassion and resilience in his community.  
 
#FridaySpotlight

Name: Fitzpatrick, Brian K.
text:
Each week, we celebrate the stories of Hometown Heroes from across our district, individuals whose actions transform lives and leave a lasting mark on our community. Today, we shine a spotlight on a remarkable young lady whose vision and compassion demonstrate what it means to lead with purpose—meet this week’s Hometown Hero, Grace Arner of Holland.
 
Grace, a talented cellist, has undertaken an extraordinary mission to ensure every child, regardless of financial circumstances, can experience the transformative power of music. She understands music is more than notes; it’s a sanctuary, a form of self-expression, and a source of healing. For children facing stress, anxiety, or hardship, music can be a lifeline—a way to process emotions, find joy, and build confidence. Yet, she also knows the cost of instruments can make this dream unattainable for many families.
 
Driven by her determination to make a difference, as part of her Eagle Scout project, Grace has set out to collect and restore instruments to their former glory, opening the door for children in our community to unleash their creativity, experience the transformative joy of music, and build a foundation for a brighter future. In addition, she has partnered with the @CouncilRockSD Music Foundation, a remarkable organization dedicated to providing scholarships for aspiring musicians and ensuring instruments reach those in need. Through this partnership, Grace has committed any unused funds from her efforts to be donated to the foundation, amplifying her impact by creating even more opportunities for students to pursue their musical dreams and carry forward the rich tradition of music education within our community.
 
Her project will culminate with a benefit recital and final donation drive at Holland Middle School on January 31st, where she has invited the community to come together to be a part of her special initiative. Along with her fellow Scouts, Grace will share her talents in a recital that embodies the very spirit of her mission: turning passion into purpose and dreams into reality.
 
Join me in applauding Grace, whose compassion, vision, and determination remind us all of the power of one person’s actions to create ripples of hope and opportunity—her efforts are a profound gift to our children and an inspiration to our community.

It is disingenuous to the American people to utilize the budget continuation process—a Continuing Resolution (CR)—to create a spending bill that has unrelated expenditures like the Francis Scott Key Bridge replacement and Medicaid DSH that are not offset.

Name: Womack, Steve

My full statement on my vote for the continuing resolution:

We were in this mess because we didn’t complete the appropriations process. I've long advocated for reforming the budget process and returning to regular order. However, I supported the CR because it’s better than the original proposal and better than a government shutdown, which would only harm the American public and kneecap President Trump as he is about to take office.

This package also received my support because it addresses the immediate needs of Third District Arkansans and includes provisions I’ve advocated for. Under my Transportation, Housing and Urban Development, and Related Agencies Subcommittee’s jurisdiction, there’s $122 million included in disaster assistance directly for Arkansans who are recovering and rebuilding from the devastating Memorial Day weekend storms. It also provides much-needed resources to Arkansas' agriculture industry dealing with crop loss, government overregulation, and high inflation. These are real-life deliverables for those I proudly represent that cannot be ignored.

I hope through a unified government beginning in the new year, Republicans will focus on righting our nation's financial ship and passing full-year appropriations as we advance President Trump's agenda.

We got it done.

Today, I was happy to pass the bipartisan government funding bill that will keep our government open through March 14th.

In this legislation, I helped secure $10 billion in economic assistance as well as $21 billion in disaster assistance for our farmers and ranchers.

Furthermore, I helped secure language to provide economic support to farmers who have been negatively impacted by Mexico's failure to deliver water to the United States in accordance with the 1944 Water Treaty.

I also secured critical funding for water infrastructure projects in the district.

As a senior member of the House Appropriations Committee, I will continue to provide the resources South Texans need to prosper.

Name: Scott, Rick
text:
🚨 NEWS: I’m incredibly proud to continue serving the great state of Florida in the 119th Congress and be a new member of the U.S. Senate Committee on Foreign Relations and the Chairman of the U.S. Senate Special Committee on Aging. I’ll also continue serving on the U.S. Senate Committee on Armed Services, the Committee on Homeland Security and Governmental Affairs and the Committee on the Budget.

As a new member of the Committee on Foreign Relations, Chairman of the Special Committee on Aging, and member of the Armed Services, Homeland Security and Governmental Affairs, and Budget committees, I will have the opportunity to fight every day in Washington for the issues most important to Florida families. During my time as Governor of Florida and U.S. Senator, I’ve made it a priority to put Florida families first and stand with our allies around the globe who believe in our way of life and freedoms. As a member of the Foreign Relations Committee, I will play a central role in continuing this work and fighting for America’s interests abroad, especially standing up for Israel as it defends itself against terrorists; holding our adversaries, like Communist China, Russia and Iran fully accountable; and standing for freedom and democracy in Cuba, Venezuela and all of Latin America. This work will be incredibly important in rightfully positioning the United States as a beacon of freedom and hope around the globe. 
 
I’d like to thank Leader-elect @SenJohnThune and Senator @MikeCrapo for working with me and my colleagues on committee assignments, ensuring that the many talented members of the Senate Republican Conference are well positioned to advance President Trump’s agenda. I will serve proudly and faithfully on these committees to protect the best interests of the United States and its allies domestically and abroad, fight for our military and service members, keep Americans healthy and bring fiscal sanity back to our nation.

✔️ Keep our government open, ensuring stability and continuity for our nation.
✔️ Guarantee pay and benefits for our hero soldiers and veterans who have served and protected us.
✔️ Deliver disaster relief for our fellow Americans who were impacted by devastating natural disasters.

Name: Landsman, Greg
text:
The Social Security Fairness Act has been introduced in every Congress since the 107th.

In the 118th (this Congress), it was the most co-sponsored piece of legislation with over 300 co-sponsors in the House and over 60 in the Senate.

Name: Landsman, Greg
text: During my first year in Congress, I visited the National Archives where I saw the discharge petition for the 1964 Civil Rights Act.…

Name: Landsman, Greg
text:
President Johnson and MLK (and most members of Congress) wanted the civil rights bill passed, but congressional leadership wasn’t ready. 

So they went around them with a discharge petition.

Name: Landsman, Greg
text:
Retired teachers, firefighters, police officers, & letter carriers nationwide have called on Congress to pass the Social Security Fairness Act.

For us, it was Melissa, a retiring public school teacher. Hundreds of calls like hers showed us how this bill could change lives.

Name: Landsman, Greg
text:
For weeks, I made the case with my colleagues. 

On Sept. 10th, I joined the bill’s co-leads, @RepSpanberger and @RepGarretGraves, and we launched the discharge petition. 

I was proudly the third signature.😊

Name: Landsman, Greg
text:
As I listened to the folks at the National Archives tell us the story of the discharge petition’s role in the 1964 Civil Rights Act, I thought of callers like Melissa and decided: 

We’re going to do this with the Social Security Fairness Act.

Name: Landsman, Greg
text:
We needed 218 signatures for it to move forward. In nine days, we had them. 

The House passed the Social Security Fairness Act with a vote of 327-75.

Name: Landsman, Greg
text:
It was time to get the Senate to call the vote.

Tonight, it passed the Senate.

text:
The continuing resolution that passed the Senate and House tonight was far from perfect, but it delivered several key wins for America: keeping government open (meaning our troops and other essential personnel get paid through the holiday season), delivering relief for our farmers and bringing disaster relief to communities devastated by hurricanes this fall. 

Our budget and appropriations process in Congress has been dysfunctional for far too long. It’s my hope that come next year, we can return to doing appropriations the way we should: working through the committee process and bringing these bills to the floor before the end of the fiscal year, instead of continually kicking the can down the road with a series of CRs and shutdown threats.

text: In addition to preserving pay for our brave men and women in uniform, the continuing resolution I voted for tonight includes an important $110 billion disaster-relief package. Name: Collins, Mike
text:
On #ThisDayInHistory in 1945, General George S. Patton, commander of the U.S. 3rd Army, died from injuries sustained in a car accident at the age of 60.

A product of a military family, Patton graduated from West Point and competed in the 1912 Olympics as the first American pentathlete. He later served in WW1's Tank Corps, advocating for tank warfare. During WWII, he led successful campaigns, including the capture of Palermo, Sicily, in 1943, and the relief of Bastogne during the Battle of the Bulge in 1944, using unconventional strategies.

Patton was known for his boldness and forceful leadership, famously stating, "We herd sheep. We drive cattle. We lead people. Lead me, follow me, or get out of my way." His bluntness and controversial behavior often put his career at risk, most notably when he slapped a soldier suffering from "shell shock," leading to public backlash. However, General Dwight Eisenhower and General George Marshall intervened, and Patton returned to active duty. He continued to lead with audacity, driving German forces across the Rhine and advancing into southern Germany in 1945.

text:
The Continuing Resolution that passed last night was better than the 1547-page disaster dumped in our laps just a few days ago. 

Unfortunately, it still contained $111 billion in deficit spending, with no corresponding cuts. I could not vote for it in good conscience. 

The American people just returned Donald Trump to the White House and gave the GOP control of both the House and Senate in large part because they were hurting from runaway inflation caused by Joe Biden’s reckless federal spending. They are counting on us to stop it. 

We should not turn around and continue Biden’s mistakes. 
 
Our national debt will soon exceed the size of our economy. We have annual budget deficits totaling nearly $2 trillion and this year the federal government will spend more on interest payments to service our debt than we have spent on our own national defense.

As my friend Elon Musk recently said, “what the federal government does not receive in direct revenue they make up for in inflation. They just print money. So, all federal spending is taxation.”

Americans shouldn’t be losing their money to more federal spending or the invisible tax of inflation.  

I look forward to working with President Trump and DOGE to cut wasteful government programs, restore fiscal responsibility, and allow American families to prosper.

Name: Cloud, Michael
text:
Reflections on the End of the 118th Congress and this past week:

Before my service in Congress, I am a husband, father, grateful American citizen, and voter. I could not have been more thankful for President Trump’s reelection, and I was thrilled to finally have a candidate worth being excited to vote for.

As many of you know, my faith is what motivates everything I do, including my service in Congress and my deep love for this country. Because of that, I truly believe God sparred President Trump’s life as an act of grace, giving us the opportunity to save America.

In President Trump, we finally have a Republican leader with a sense of strategy, leverage, and a vision for reforming the swamp. This, combined with the clear mandate of the election, should afford him broad latitude on policy and strategy.

However, the corrupt DC swamp continues to fight against the MAGA agenda, and Congress is structured in a way that inherently undermines it. That’s why we must have fighters in Congress who are willing to restructure the institution and challenge DC’s addiction to reckless spending so that President Trump’s agenda has lasting permanence.

When President Trump made it clear that he wanted to address the debt ceiling now—rather than waiting for the January/February reconciliation package many of us were working on—the answer for myself and many others who consistently oppose debt ceiling increases was, if the President wants it, then yes. We understood and respected President Trump’s strategic leverage play. The only remaining question was: How?

As I made clear to the Speaker in his office, I trust President Trump and his team. But I do not trust Congress—a body that has long been willing to raise the debt ceiling without delivering reforms. I, along with others, sought a commitment from fellow Republicans to ensure we would follow through on Trump’s much-needed spending reforms when the time came.

While we made significant progress, ultimately, we were unable to secure this commitment in the few hours we had to work before the vote.

Adding to the problem was the fact that we had an agreement from Speaker Johnson to pass the CR as single-subject bills which he retracted on after meeting with Democrat leader Hakeem Jeffries behind closed doors. This led to more House Democrats voting for the CR than Republicans.

The chaos of this past week was both predictable and avoidable. Weeks ago, I and others warned of these pinch points and urged leadership to involve members in crafting solutions. Unfortunately, we were ignored and locked out of the process. It wasn’t the rank-and-file members who failed this week—it was a failure of leadership that brought us here.

Come January, we will need to revisit how Congress operates to ensure it is structured to deliver President Trump’s MAGA agenda. Whether that requires personnel changes, process reforms, or both will be a critical discussion we must have.

May God bless you and your family this Christmas season. I look forward to January 20th and the beginning of a renewed American Renaissance.

Name: McGovern, James P.
text:
2/ Trump didn’t get the one thing he wanted in the government funding deal: A debt ceiling increase so he could give himself and his billionaire friends a tax break. 

But you know who got exactly what he wanted? Elon Musk...

Name: McGovern, James P.
text: 1/ The one big thing nobody is talking about: Did Elon want to shut the government down because of his business deals with China? A thread... 🧵

Name: McGovern, James P.
text: 3/ The original funding bill (that he killed) included what’s called an “outbound investment” provision—which would limit & screen U.S. money flowing to China. That would have made it easier to keep cutting-edge AI and quantum computing tech—as well as jobs—in America.

Name: McGovern, James P.
text: 4/ But Elon had a problem. His second-largest market is China. He’s building huge factories there. His bottom line depends on staying in China’s good graces. He wants to build an AI data center there too—which could endanger U.S. security. He’s been bending over backwards to ingratiate himself with Chinese leaders.

Name: McGovern, James P.
text: 5/ So what did Elon do? He tanked the whole thing—telling Trump to oppose it, and threatening to primary anyone who voted yes. And to cover his tracks, he claimed it was about “spending” (even though Trump wanted to suspend the debt limit for unlimited spending).

Name: McGovern, James P.
text:
6/ What did Trump get out of all this? Nothing. 

But President Musk got what he wanted: The ability to sell out the U.S. so he could make money in China. It’s all one big game to these guys. I hate it, because they’re hurting regular people.

Name: McGovern, James P.
text: 7/ This time, Democrats won. We stopped Trump from being able to cut taxes for billionaires. But Elon’s ability to kill a bill on China that would hurt his bank account shows you exactly who Republicans work for. It’s not you. It’s the billionaires and special interests who don’t give a shit about you. Democrats can win—but we need to show up & expose this corruption every. single. time.

Name: Fong, Vince
text: Stratolaunch makes history with its first fully reusable hypersonic flight test of the Talon A-2 vehicle which took off yesterday from the Mojave Air and Space Port, located in California’s 20th District. Our region continues to lead the way for America to explore, test, and advance new flight technologies – from Chuck Yeager’s test flight breaking the sound barrier almost 80 years ago to NASA’s X-59 quiet supersonic flight engine testing last month. This historic flight signifies a new era of hypersonic flight technology, where traveling at faster speeds may soon become a reality thanks to American entrepreneurship and innovation, and I enjoyed learning more about next steps from Stratolaunch when I visited Mojave last week.  Congratulations to Zack Krevor and the Stratolaunch team on this incredible accomplishment!

Name: Fitzpatrick, Brian K.
text:
Today, I was honored to help celebrate the remarkable Guido DiFrancesco of Telford, a @USArmy World War II D-Day Veteran, on his 100th birthday! Guido embodies the resilience and courage of the Greatest Generation. Forced to leave high school during the Depression to support his family, he never let challenges define him—earning his diploma at 93 years young after retiring at 85! 

From storming Omaha Beach on D-Day to serving his community as a dedicated member of the Warrington Lions, Guido has lived a life of extraordinary service, hard work, and love. A devoted family man, he continues to inspire his children, 10 grandchildren, and 25 great-grandchildren with his unwavering love, enduring strength, and encouragement to serve others.

Join me in wishing Guido a very happy birthday and thanking him for his service, sacrifice, and example as a true American hero!

Name: Collins, Mike
text:
On #ThisDayInHistory in 1986 after nine days and four minutes, the experimental aircraft 𝑉𝑜𝑦𝑎𝑔𝑒𝑟 completed the first nonstop flight around the world on a single fuel load. 

It covered 25,012 miles, starting and ending at Edwards Air Force Base in California. The plane was made of lightweight materials and carried over three times its weight in fuel with had a wingspan of 111 feet.

The flight began on December 14, with 𝑉𝑜𝑦𝑎𝑔𝑒𝑟 so heavy with fuel that its wings scraped the ground during takeoff. Despite encountering severe turbulence from tropical storms and technical issues, including an engine failure, the aircraft managed to stay airborne.

When 450 miles remained, the plane's engine failed, but an alternate engine was started, allowing it to continue its journey. 𝑉𝑜𝑦𝑎𝑔𝑒𝑟 landed safely with only a few gallons of fuel left. It is now on display at the National Air and Space Museum in Washington, D.C.

The holiday season is an opportunity to cherish our time with family.

(Thread 🧵)

Name: Schiff, Adam B.
text:
Dr. Wang Bingzhang has spent 22 years in solitary confinement.
 
His crime? Advocating for democracy in China.
 
The CCP abducted him in Vietnam in 2002, accusing him of espionage and terrorism – charges human rights groups have denounced as fabricated.

Name: Schiff, Adam B.
text:
Dr. Wang is a pioneer of China’s pro-democracy movement. He founded China Spring, the first pro-democracy magazine outside of China, in 1982.
 
This year, Freedom House honored him with its Freedom Award.
 
He turns 77 on December 30. Alone. In a prison cell.

Name: Schiff, Adam B.
text:
Mr. Ding Jiaxi, a human rights lawyer, spent his career advocating for the rights of China’s most vulnerable.
 
After calling for transparency and exposing corruption, he has spent much of the last decade imprisoned.
 
This month marks 5 years since his most recent arrest.

Name: Schiff, Adam B.
text:
Freedom of speech and expression are basic human rights.
 
The Chinese government must release Dr. Wang, Mr. Ding, and all prisoners of conscience. 
 
And I will continue to advocate for these innocent men and others to be returned home to their families.

Name: Collins, Mike
text:
On #ThisDayInHistory in 1814, the Treaty of Ghent officially ended the War of 1812 between the United States and Great Britain. 

The treaty stipulated that conquered territories would be returned and established commissions to settle the U.S.-Canada border. Despite not addressing the main issues that sparked the war—British interference with American trade and impressment of U.S. sailors—it was seen as a diplomatic victory for the U.S. as it opened the Great Lakes region for expansion.

The war began in June 1812, triggered by British economic blockades, the forced enlistment of American sailors, and British support for Native American attacks on the U.S. frontier. Initial American invasions of Canada were unsuccessful, but the U.S. Navy achieved several victories at sea. In 1814, after Napoleon's defeat, Britain focused more on the war, capturing Washington, D.C., and burning key government buildings. However, the British were repelled at Fort McHenry, inspiring the writing of the "Star-Spangled Banner."

The turning point came in September 1814 when the U.S. won a crucial naval battle at Lake Champlain, forcing British forces to retreat from the northeast. Though news of the treaty’s signing reached the U.S. too late to stop the Battle of New Orleans, where General Andrew Jackson's forces achieved a stunning victory, the simultaneous news of the peace settlement and the triumph at New Orleans boosted American national pride and unity.

Name: Auchincloss, Jake
text: I visited Naval Submarine Base New London, and surrounding facilities, to learn about the construction and warfighting of the U.S. submarine fleet. American nuclear submarines are strategic gamechangers whose low profile and lethality make them pillars of our maritime power. I spoke with submarine commanders and strategists about the cutting edge of tactics, competing with Russia & China, and working with Australia, Japan, and the United Kingdom. I also toured the shipyards with top engineers to see the challenges and progress in rebuilding the submarine industrial base after divestment following the Cold War. Building a nuclear power plant that can cruise around the world and launch missiles underwater – without being detected – is an unmatched feat of industrial engineering. It’s also a major opportunity for southern New England’s economy, as much of the supply chain clusters in this region.

Name: Pingree, Chellie
text: Lighthouse keepers would often light an extra lantern to help guide sailors safely ashore on Christmas Eve. For those who lived on-site with their families, a feast of seafood was a common way to celebrate. Calm seas on Christmas Eve were seen as a good omen for the year ahead.

Name: Pingree, Chellie
text:
Now, whenever I see a lighthouse all aglow, I’ll think of these traditions, and how the holiday spirit continues to be a beacon for our coastal communities—and everyone who calls Maine home.

Merry Christmas Eve to all.

(And thanks to Dennis Tangney, Jr. for the amazing photo.) https://t.co/W3ZNyyQn7A
